{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2ddf8d82-aa27-4181-9ba1-8a364f926ba9","content":"Use `dotnet watch test` — it re-runs tests automatically whenever you save a file. You can filter to just the failing test:\n\n```\ndotnet watch test --filter \"RemoveStock_ExceedsAvailable_ThrowsException\"\n```\n\nWant me to start it up now? Meanwhile, the bug is clear — `RemoveStock` (line 36-37) subtracts without checking if there's enough stock. It never throws. The fix is to add a guard:\n\n```csharp\npublic void RemoveStock(string sku, int quantity)\n{\n    var current = _stock.GetValueOrDefault(sku);\n    if (quantity > current)\n        throw new InvalidOperationException(\"Insufficient stock\");\n    _stock[sku] = current - quantity;\n}\n```\n\nWant me to apply the fix and run the watcher so you can see it pass?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ce858fad-8a72-41f5-9bc9-03d31e37c650","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to set up hot reload for their test project. With .NET and MSTest, they can use `dotnet watch test` or, since they're using MSTest 3.8.0 with the Microsoft Testing Platform runner (configured in global.json), they can use `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test`.\n\nLet me check what's available. With .NET 10 and Microsoft Testing Platform, there's `dotnet test --hotreload` which is a newer feature. But `dotnet watch test` has been available for a while.\n\nActually, let me think about this. The `dotnet watch` tool can be used with `dotnet watch test` to re-run tests when files change. \n\nWith Microsoft Testing Platform in .NET 10, there might be additional hot reload capabilities, but the most straightforward approach is `dotnet watch test`, which watches for file changes and automatically reruns the tests.","outputTokens":629,"requestId":"E3CE:BC837:1895DB8:1B80E12:6A05298D"},"id":"1a7f7a74-356d-4138-9482-01018308e4b8","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:47:09.623Z","parentId":"6f41aca7-dc29-40ca-b6f5-0b0afec7d23e"}
